LAB EXERCISE 6: Identify and explain three common application security vulnerabilities. Suggest
possible solutions.
Answer-
1. SQL Injection (SQLi)
Explanation

SQL Injection occurs when an attacker inserts malicious SQL queries into input fields (like login forms) to manipulate the database. This can allow unauthorized access to sensitive data.

Example

Entering ' OR '1'='1 in a login field to bypass authentication.

Solutions

Use prepared statements (parameterized queries)

Validate and sanitize user input

Use ORM frameworks

Limit database permissions

2. Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
Explanation

XSS happens when attackers inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal cookies, session data, or redirect users to malicious sites.

Types

Stored XSS

Reflected XSS

DOM-based XSS

Solutions

Validate and sanitize user inputs

Escape output before rendering

Use Content Security Policy (CSP)

Avoid inline JavaScript

3. Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)
Explanation

CSRF tricks users into performing unwanted actions on a web application where they are already authenticated (e.g., transferring money without their consent).

Example

A malicious link that triggers a bank transaction when clicked.

Solutions

Use CSRF tokens

Implement same-site cookies

Require re-authentication for sensitive actions

Validate request origin

